    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_08_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline> 
                     <date when="1813-08" cert="high"><unclear></unclear> Au. 13</date></dateline> <note>90</note>
                    
                    My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">Sir</persName></opener>
                <p> 
                   
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> has as<lb/>
                    usual expressed my<lb/>
                    sentiments so fully<lb/>
                    that I have nothing <lb/>
                    to add except my<lb/>
                    individual thanks<lb/>
                    for your kindness<lb/>
                    &amp; attentions while<lb/>
                    we were in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    My <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">better half</persName><lb/>
                    feels as I do, and<lb/>
                    would say so with<lb/>
                    her own pen if it<lb/>
                    could be doubted -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    I shall do every<lb/>
                    thing in my power<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_08_page02.jpg"/>
                    to assist <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> in<lb/>
                    her attempt to popularize<lb/>
                    your <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">Bentham</persName> - <lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    This can be done<lb/>
                    more effectually by<lb/>
                    retrenching than by<lb/>
                    addition - In fact<lb/>
                    what can be done,<lb/>
                    but to leave out<lb/>
                    the formal divisions<lb/>
                    and all the minor<lb/>
                    definitions? --<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    The volatile effusions<lb/>
                    of imagination may<lb/>
                    be condensed but<lb/>
                    solid sense cannot<lb/>
                    easily be compressed<lb/>
                        
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_08_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>91</note>
                    To review such a<lb/>
                    book the principal<lb/>
                    object should be to<lb/>
                    show the utility of<lb/>
                    a scientific and<lb/>
                    elaborate classification<lb/>
                    to point out the<lb/>
                    practical advantages<lb/>
                    of a complete detailed<lb/>
                    system &amp; to elucidate<lb/>
                    these statements<lb/>
                    by every thing that<lb/>
                    may amuse and<lb/>
                    interest general<lb/>
                    readers --<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                    To laugh good humoredly<lb/>
                    at some of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BentJ1">Benthams</persName><lb/>
                    extravagancies --  To<lb/>
                        
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1813_08_page04.jpg"/>
                    show that they do not<lb/>
                    derogate from the<lb/>
                    general excellence of<lb/>
                    his designs - and<lb/>
                    to point out how<lb/>
                    ably his commentator<lb/>
                    has selected, <choice><orig>exempli-<lb/>
                    fied</orig><reg>exemplified</reg></choice>, arranged and<lb/>
                    adorned the whole<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> will endeavour<lb/>
                    to sow the seeds of<lb/>
                    political economy<lb/>
                    in the young minds<lb/>
                    whom she <del>endeavors</del> <add>is attempting</add><lb/>
                    to instruct by Early<lb/>
                    lessons -- Familiarity<lb/>
                    with terms &amp; the habit<lb/>
                    of short &amp; accurate reasoning<lb/>
                    are the best preparations for science<lb/></p>
                    <closer>adieu<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">RLE</persName><lb/></closer>
                    
                
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
